From evan at telly.org  Fri Jun 26 07:18:39 2015
From: evan at telly.org (Evan Leibovitch)
Date: Fri, 26 Jun 2015 09:18:39 +0200
Subject: [GTALUG] Request for printer recommendations
In-Reply-To: <558CBC64.7030506@gmail.com>
References: <alpine.LRH.2.02.1412081216400.4080@redclaw.mimosa.com>
 <CAHcykVq7_g3u8R__1yYnk=SgVhnzbMLnXyfU6L7Xs3N9ms4SEQ@mail.gmail.com>
 <CAHcykVpmba3xcKY2wCYkEAXsiYrDtQ9i_Lr2ZQ7RADsG+d1nZw@mail.gmail.com>
 <558C389A.8080302@mylesbraithwaite.com> <558C4132.7020908@pair.com>
 <558CB392.5010406@sobac.com>
 <c586d5af0d529fd62592b108fbdf3553.squirrel@webmail.ee.ryerson.ca>
 <558CBC64.7030506@gmail.com>
Message-ID: <CAMguqh3SRhRd6XF_wvYo_w-bm-N6aOPGn9Z+kun0rNjcRAqb-g@mail.gmail.com>

Generally, I buy by brand since the model numbers change so much. Within
brands, I try to find sources (such as Consumer Reports) that measure
objective criteria such as cost-per-page and sharpness.

I have never gone wrong with Brother or HP. HP support for Linux is more
full-featured <http://hplipopensource.com/hplip-web/index.html>, especially
if you can use an Internet connection rather than USB, but it occasionally
contains closed-source bits for some cheaper models. Brother support is
more vanilla but pretty solid.

I have heard from associates having success with Samsung printers under
Linux but have no first hand experience.

On the other side are brands to avoid, that are indifferent at best to
Linux and hostile at worst. These are Canon and Lexmark.

On 26 June 2015 at 04:43, Stewart C. Russell <scruss at gmail.com> wrote:

> On 2015-06-25 10:11 PM, phiscock at ee.ryerson.ca wrote:
